stylometry: Decision theory is a method we can use to evaluate the probabilities of an outcome and the associated payoffs of the different outcomes to locate the most profitable solution. Payoff tables do that by taking a number of decisions (say you need somewhere to live that you can resell in the next 5 years and you have to decide between a beachfront condo, a shack in the woods, or a large mansion on state st.). Each decision takes a different amount to purchase in the first place, each has a different probability of being profitable (good or bad real estate market), and each will offer a different payoff after you sell it in 5 years. Buying the mansion may seem like it would be profitable to sell it than the other properties, but after the initial price you paid for it and the real estate market crashes, you may even loose money on it in the end. Likewise the shack in the woods may be cheap at first to purchase, but after you fix it up and the real estate market picks up, its now worth a lot more than when you purchased it. So by organizing each of the options in payoff table will allow you to locate the most profitable decision based on the probability of a favorable/unfavorable real estate market as well as the EMV (expected monetary vaule) of each option. That way you can make the best decision.
